Introdution¶

For this problem, we used Default of Credit Card Clients Dataset. In this data set, there are 30,000 examples and 24 features, and the goal is to estimate whether a person will default (fail to pay) their credit card bills; this column is labeled "default.payment.next.month" in the data. The rest of the columns can be used as features. We may take some ideas and compare our results with the associated research paper, which is available through the UBC library.

The problem at hand involves binary classification, specifically predicting whether a credit card client will default or not. The dataset in question is moderately sized, while the number of features is relatively small, making it a problem with a small dimensionality. Although all features are numerically encoded, certain ones, such as sex and marriage, appear to possess categorical characteristics.

There are 25 variables/columns in this dataset. The target variable is "default.payment.next.month" which is a binary variable with value 1 for yes (default) and 0 for no (not-default). Other variables that potentially can be considered as features are as follows:

  • ID: a unique identification code for each customer. As each row is exclusively for one customer and the data is tidy, this varaible does not need to be considered as a feature. We can simply drop it.
  • LIMIT_BAL: a numeric variable which shows the credit amount given to the individual or family.
  • SEX: a binary (1 as male and 2 as female) variable.
  • EDUCATION: an ordinal variable (1 for graduate school, 2 for university, 3 for high school, 4 for others (apparently lower education than 1 ,2, and 3), and 5 and 6 are unknown). We need to deal with the 5 and 6. Moreover, there are 14 examples with the EDUCATION value of zero, which is not defined in the dataset description. According to the response of professor "Cheng Yeh", the source delegate, to a question in this regard, I am going to consider 0,4,5, and 6 as "others". For more info see here, the discussion under the dataset at Kaggle.
  • MARRIAGE: a categorical variable; 1 for married, 2 for single, and 3 for other. There are 54 examples with the MARRIAGE value of zero, which is not defined in the dataset description. Following professor "Cheng Yeh", I consider all zeros as "others". For more info see here.
  • AGE: an integer variable with the range of 21 to 79. I would consider this variable as a numeric feature.
  • PAY_i: PAY_0, PAY_2, PAY_3, PAY_4, PAY_5, PAY_6: all are ordinal features with same regular values

Value -2 is not described in the data description. Following professor "Cheng Yeh", I consider all -2 values as "no cunsumption". For more info see here.

  • BILL_AMTi: BILL_AMT1, BILL_AMT2, BILL_AMT3, BILL_AMT4, BILL_AMT5, BILL_AMT6: Numeric feature, bill statement amount
  • PAY_AMT1: PAY_AMT1, PAY_AMT2,PAY_AMT3,PAY_AMT4,PAY_AMT5,PAY_AMT6: Numeric feature, previous payment amount

There are some non-defined values in Eduacation (and some other columns).

Out[ ]:

Let's rename the target column "default.payment.next.month" to "target"

In [ ]:
df.rename(columns = {'default.payment.next.month':'target'}, inplace= True)

According to professor "Cheng Yeh" to a query in this regard, all EDUCATION values 0, 4, 5, and 6 should be considered as "others". For more info see here. So, I change all these value to "4" to be consistent.

In [ ]:
df['EDUCATION'] = df['EDUCATION'].replace(0, int(4))
df['EDUCATION'] = df['EDUCATION'].replace(5, int(4))
df['EDUCATION'] = df['EDUCATION'].replace(6, int(4))

  • First, we checked the distribution of some features across different target classes. The plots show we are facing class imbalance in this project. So, the accuracy does not seem to be a good metrics here. We need to focus on either of precision, recall, or f1 scores. Because in this specific project fale negatives are more crucial than false positives, we better to weigh more on recall metric.
  • Then, I tried to compare the distribution of different features across target to see which featurs can be more helpful in this study:
    • The education distribution shows that as the education level of customers increases the probability of default simply decreases. See the difference between the distributions across different targets for each level of education.
    • The probability of default in low limit balances seems to be more than for higher limit balances.
    • We can conclude that features like education, limit balance, marriage and pays seems to be good features to deffrentiate between default and no-default calsses. However, it does not seem that bill amount features are powerful in calssification here.
  • Then I illustrated the correlation across features. There are high correlation between bill amount features, and pays. In other words we have to deal with colinearity here in this project.

Initial observations:

  • The number of features is limited.
  • Class imbalance is present and requires addressing. The chosen evaluation metric is macro-average F1 score, which gives equal weight to both classes.
  • The feature ranges vary significantly, necessitating standardization.
  • Collinearity is observed among some features.
  • Several outliers are present in the data.
  • The data appears to be messy and inconsistent with the provided description.
    • There is uncertainty regarding education levels 5 and 6.
    • The meaning of values -2 and 0 for PAY_* features is unclear.
  • Notable outliers are observed in features such as 'EDUCATION', 'MARRIAGE', and 'PAY_\d*'.

def mean_std_cross_val_scores(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs):
    """
    Returns mean and std of cross validation

    Parameters
    ----------
    model :
        scikit-learn model
    X_train : numpy array or pandas DataFrame
        X in the training data
    y_train :
        y in the training data

    Returns
    ----------
        pandas Series with mean scores from cross_validation
    """

    scores = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs)

    mean_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).mean()
    std_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).std()
    out_col = []

    for i in range(len(mean_scores)):
        out_col.append((f"%0.3f (+/- %0.3f)" % (mean_scores[i], std_scores[i])))

    return pd.Series(data=out_col, index=mean_scores.index)

Summary of observations

Hyperparameter optimization seems to help with random forests as well as LightGBM. The scores for both models seem very similar. But we pick LightGBM because

  • it seems to be less overfitting
  • it's much faster
  • the standard deviation is smaller compared to random forest.

Concluding remarks¶

All our models beat the baseline. Our best model was LightGBM classifier with tuned hyperparameters. It achieved cross-validation macro-average f1 score of 0.707. The scores do not seem to overfit much; the gap between mean train score (0.719) and mean cross-validation score (0.707) is not big. These scores are very similar to the tuned random forest. But random forest seems to overfit. Also, it's much slower than LightGBM. So picked LightGBM model as our final model.

We observed the macro-average f1 score of 0.695 using this model on the held out test set, which is in line with mean cross-validation macro-average f1-score (0.707). So there doesn't seem to be severe optimization bias here.

We observed that L1 feature selection helped a tiny bit for random forests. But we did not observe any improvement in LightGBM scores with feature selection in the pipeline. In general, we have small number of features in this problem and feature selection doesn't seem crucial.

Our analysis of feature importances shows that our PAY_\d{0,2}, LIMIT_*, and PAY_AMT* variables seems to be most important features. Although SEX feature doesn't show up as one of the most important features, depending upon the context it might be a good idea to drop this feature from our analysis.

Other ideas¶

  • Preprocessing and feature engineering

    • The BILL_AMT* and PAY_AMT* variables are the bill amount, and amount paid, respectively. We could try making new features by subtracting or otherwise combining these, which would be the amount you paid relative to the amount owed.
    • There are a number of collinear features in the dataset, especially, our PAY_\d{0,5} features, which are one of the topmost important features. We could create new features by combining these features.
    • More data cleaning would probably help.
    • In my opinion, data cleaning and feature engineering are very important here.

  • More careful hyperparameter optimization

    • Because of limited time, we did not carry out extensive hyperparameter optimization. For instance, we didn't carry out hyperparameter optimization with the XGBoost model. It might be worth exploring this area a bit more.
